use of self-generation was turned into an indispensable determination by Fichte and his successors: philosophical knowledge can claim absolute certainty only if it can prove that it generates itself in logically accountable procedures. This self-generating philosophy—also known as Idealism—was in turn accompanied by a revaluation of the origin of language, notably by Herder and by Humboldt, who attempted to formulate self-generation as the philosophical foundation for a future Science of Language. The book concludes by demonstrating that the biological, philosophical, and linguistic problematic of self-generation is at the heart of Goethe's novel Elective Affinities and Beaumarchais's The Marriage of Figaro.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362389740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503623897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503623897/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles